Question:
Remove duplicate strings from a list.
Input:
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("dog", "cat", "dog", "bird");

Solution:

Java 8 Streams remove duplicate strings using distinct() intermediate operation. For input ["dog", "cat", "dog", "bird"], produces unique ["dog", "cat", "bird"].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). Apply distinct() to retain first occurrence of each unique value. Collect to new list with Collectors.toList().

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class RemoveDuplicates {
    public static List<String> removeDuplicates(List<String> strings) {
        return strings.stream()
                      .distinct()
                      .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> list = Arrays.asList("dog", "cat", "dog", "bird");
        List<String> unique = removeDuplicates(list);
        System.out.println(unique);  // [dog, cat, bird]
    }
}

Original list unchanged; returns new ArrayList with uniques in encounter order.

#Thought Process
distinct() uses equals() and hashCode() to deduplicate, keeping first seen. Stateful intermediate; stable order. collect(toList()) terminal creates list. Efficient O(n) average via HashSet internally.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Returns [].
No duplicates: Returns copy of input.
All duplicates: Returns list with first element [x].
Null list: NPE on stream(); null-check.
Null elements: Keeps first null; subsequent nulls removed (null.equals(null)=true).
Case-sensitive: "Dog" != "dog" (String equals).
Large lists: Scales well; parallel preserves first-seen semantics poorly.
